"(1) (i) crouched in the shadow of the lunar regolith, his breath fogging in the crisp air of the Shackleton Crater’s interior dome. Through the reinforced plexiglass, the colony’s control hub glowed with erratic amber light, its normally steady hum replaced by a rising tremor that vibrated through his bones. He watched as alarms flashed crimson across the main display, their symbols twisting into jagged, unfamiliar glyphs. Outside the pressurized glass, the crater’s rim was shrouded in storm clouds of ionized plasma, the sky flickering with unnatural auroras as the first signs of catastrophe pulsed into view. September 27, 2225. Samuel Parker.\n(2) (i) The cascade erupted in a shattering cascade of blue-white light, fracturing the air with a sound like a thousand glass harmonicas shattering in zero gravity. Samuel’s heart hammered against his ribs as the antimatter reaction rippled outward, painting the interior with ghostly afterimages and sending data streams spiraling into chaos. He saw the impossible—particles annihilating in midair, releasing bursts of energy that painted the walls with dancing shadows, and felt the ground thrum with the raw power of the universe itself. It was here, in this place, amid the silence of the lunar night and the terror of the unknown, Samuel that would echo through the annals of for generations. Luna Shackleton Crater Colony. witnessed a antimatter cascade."